Add zero-cost alloc-trace BP mode + FSUAE_NO_UAEFS env gate

This is a follow-up to 0001-fsuae-rpc-hook.patch.  Adds three features
used by the fast68k Verilator project to debug K1.3 + boing-disk:

1. Zero-cost-when-disabled trace BP mode.  A breakpoint installed with
   `trace=1` writes a snapshot {PC, D0, A0, A2, A3, A6, SP, 4 stack
   words} to a file per hit and silently auto-resumes — no
   debugger_active, no 50 ms ws_pulse_thread latency, ~600K hits/sec.
   Driven from inside the CPU loop via debug()'s BP-match block.

2. `fsuae_rpc_arm_bp_skip()` helper.  Re-arms `do_skip=1; debugging=1;
   SPCFLAG_BRK` after /v1/resume so externally-installed BPs actually
   fire.  Without it, deactivate_debugger() leaves `debugging=0` and
   the CPU loop never calls debug() to check BPs.

3. FSUAE_NO_UAEFS=1 env gate (expansion.cpp:expamem_reset).  Suppresses
   the K1.2/K1.3-specific KS12_BOOT_HACK that maps the UAE filesys_bank
   at $E90000.  Used for apples-to-apples chipset + alloc-pattern
   comparisons against bare-A500 RTL implementations.

The bulk of (1) and (2) lives in fsuae_rpc.cpp itself (re-applied by
copying fsuae_rpc.cpp into the source tree); this patch covers the
debug.cpp hook call-site and the expansion.cpp gate.

diff --git a/src/debug.cpp b/src/debug.cpp
index 18cb5e0b4..48249bf8c 100644
--- a/src/debug.cpp
+++ b/src/debug.cpp
@@ -81,6 +81,25 @@ static uaecptr debug_copper_pc;
 extern int audio_channel_mask;
 extern int inputdevice_logging;
 
+/* fsuae_rpc trace-BP hook (defined in fsuae_rpc.cpp).  Declared at
+ * file scope with C linkage so debug() can call it from the BP-match
+ * block without an in-function `extern "C"` (illegal in C++). */
+extern "C" int fsuae_rpc_trace_bp_hook (int slot, uae_u32 pc);
+
+/* fsuae_rpc: arm the BP machinery from outside debug.cpp.  The
+ * in-process debugger normally sets `do_skip = 1` + SPCFLAG_BRK when
+ * the user types `g` to resume from a paused state.  When the RPC
+ * client installs a BP without ever entering the debugger, that
+ * priming step never happens, and the CPU loop never calls debug() to
+ * check BPs.  This helper wires it up so externally-installed BPs fire
+ * normally. */
+extern "C" void fsuae_rpc_arm_bp_skip (void)
+{
+	do_skip = 1;
+	debugging = 1;
+	set_special (SPCFLAG_BRK);
+}
+
 void deactivate_debugger (void)
 {
 	debugger_active = 0;
@@ -5332,10 +5351,22 @@ void debug (void)
 					continue;
 				if (bpnodes[i].addr == pc) {
 					bp = 1;
-					console_out_f (_T("Breakpoint at %08X\n"), pc);
 					break;
 				}
 			}
+			/* fsuae_rpc trace-BP hook: a trace BP captures regs to a
+			 * file and silently auto-resumes — no console output, no
+			 * interactive debugger, no client poll required.  When no
+			 * trace BPs are installed, the hook returns 0 immediately
+			 * (single conditional + return), so this is zero-cost
+			 * when the trace feature is unused. */
+			if (bp) {
+				if (fsuae_rpc_trace_bp_hook (i, pc)) {
+					bp = 0;
+				} else {
+					console_out_f (_T("Breakpoint at %08X\n"), pc);
+				}
+			}
 
 			if (skipaddr_doskip) {
 				if (skipaddr_start == pc)
